%
% Sample input deck demonstrating set(ancestor_subsume), ported
% from Otter.  Ancestor subsumption refines ordinary subsumption
% for proof-elegance work: when two clauses are alphabetic
% variants (mutually subsume each other), ordinary subsumption
% discards whichever arrived later, regardless of derivation
% length.  Ancestor subsumption preserves the variant with the
% shorter proof, at the cost of retaining one extra clause per
% blocked subsumption.
%
% Blocking a subsumption is always sound (keeps more clauses, not
% fewer); it only costs search performance.  Turn it on for
% proof-shortening work or iterative resonance/hint pipelines
% where short derivations of intermediate lemmas matter.
%
% The companion flag set(proof_weight) switches the tie-breaking
% metric from proof_length (distinct ancestors, DAG size) to
% proof tree weight (input-clause leaves, counted with
% multiplicity).  Default is proof_length.
%
% See Fitelson (2026) Section 4 for a detailed treatment, and
% Otter's clause.c lines 1188-1204 for the original implementation.
%

set(ancestor_subsume).
% set(proof_weight).   % uncomment to use tree-leaf count instead

formulas(sos).
  e * x = x.
  x' * x = e.
  (x * y) * z = x * (y * z).
  x * x = e.
end_of_list.

formulas(goals).
  x * y = y * x.
end_of_list.
